  "prompt": "What can I do if my new CA driver's license hasn't come in the mail?",
  "response": "If your new California driver's license hasn't arrived in the mail, here are the steps you can take:\n\n1. **Check the Processing Time**:\n   - The California Department of Motor Vehicles (DMV) typically processes and mails licenses within **3-4 weeks** after your application. If it\u2019s still within this timeframe, wait a bit longer.\n\n2. **Verify Your Address**:\n   - Ensure you provided the correct mailing address to the DMV. If your address has changed or was incorrect, you may need to update it with the DMV.\n\n3. **Wait for the Extended Deadline**:\n   - If you applied for a Real ID or renewed your license, the DMV may allow you to use your temporary paper license longer if there are delays.\n\n4. **Track Your License**:\n   - If you ordered your license through the DMV website, you may be able to track its status online. Check your confirmation email for details.\n\n5. **Contact the DMV**:\n   - If it\u2019s been more than **4 weeks** and your license hasn\u2019t arrived, contact the DMV:\n     - **Call**: 1-800-777-0133.\n     - **Visit**: Go to a DMV office and bring your temporary paper license or application receipt.\n     - **Explain**: Inform them that your license hasn\u2019t arrived and request assistance.\n\n6. **Request a Replacement**:\n   - If your license was lost in the mail, you may need to request a replacement:\n     - **Online**: Log in to your DMV account.\n     - **In-Person**: Visit a DMV office.\n     - A replacement fee may apply.\n\n7. **Check for Mail Issues**:\n   - Confirm with your local post office if there\u2019s been any issue with mail delivery to your address.\n\nBy following these steps, you should be able to resolve the issue and receive your driver's license.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
